Rishikesh:

Lakshman Jhula: A suspension bridge across the river Ganges1.
Triveni Ghat: A ghat where three rivers meet and a sacred bathing spot2.
Delhi:

India Gate: A war memorial located astride the Rajpath3.
Flagship Chaudhary Palace Near Lotus Temple: A landmark near the Lotus Temple4.
Agra:

Taj Mahal: An ivory-white marble mausoleum on the right bank of the Yamuna river5.
Agra Fort: A historical fort in the city of Agra6.
Jaipur:

Hawa Mahal: A palace in Jaipur, so named because it was essentially a high screen wall built so the women of the royal household could observe street festivals while unseen from the outside7.
Nahargarh Fort: Located on the Aravalli range of hills, it provides an excellent view of Aravalli hills and the Amer Fort8.
Udaipur:

Saheliyon-ki-Bari: A major garden and a popular tourist space in Udaipur9.
Udaipur City Palace: A palace complex situated in the city of Udaipur that offers a panoramic view of the city and its surroundings10.
Mumbai:

Gateway of India: An arch-monument built in the early twentieth century in the city of Mumbai, in the Indian state of Maharashtra11.
Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus: A historic terminal train station and UNESCO World Heritage Site in Mumbai, Maharashtra, India12.
Chennai:

St George Fort: The first English fortress in India, founded in 1644 at Chennai, by the British East India Company13.
Marina Beach: A natural urban beach along the Bay of Bengal, part of the Indian Ocean14.
Please note that this is not an exhaustive list and there are many more landmarks to explore in these cities. Enjoy your trip! ðŸ˜Š

